![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/62e627fa-9987-4340-9983-8a3ec27879bc/wwe-the-rock-raw-1680x945.jpg)

The Wrestling Observer is reporting The Rock's involvement during the build-up to WrestleMania XL and Paul Heyman's Hall of Fame speech are considered to be the end of the “PG-Era” in WWE.

The PG era, characterized by a more family-friendly and advertiser-friendly product, has been a defining feature of the company's programming for over a decade. During this period, WWE aimed to appeal to a broader audience, toning down some of the edgier elements that had been prevalent in previous eras.

However, recent developments have sparked discussions about whether WWE is poised to transition away from the PG era. One such development is the involvement of Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson in the build-up to WrestleMania XL. As one of the most electrifying figures in sports entertainment history, The Rock's return to the ring always generates immense excitement among fans. His presence in the lead-up to WrestleMania XL saw a departure from the more sanitized approach of the PG era, returning to the more vulgar yet larger-than-life storytelling and characters that defined previous eras.

Additionally, Paul Heyman's Hall of Fame speech has been cited as another indication of a potential shift in WWE's creative direction. Heyman, at one point in his speech, tells any naysayers they can “**SUCK MY F\*CKING D**\***CK”**

While these events have sparked speculation about the end of the PG era, it's essential to note that WWE has not made any official announcements regarding a shift in its programming approach.

The company's upcoming deal with Netflix has also been cited as a factor that could have influenced its new creative direction. As WWE explores new avenues for distribution and content creation, there is speculation that it may be more willing to take creative risks and cater to a more mature audience.

Ultimately, whether or not WWE is indeed nearing the end of the PG era remains to be seen. The Rock's involvement in WrestleMania XL and Paul Heyman's Hall of Fame speech may be indicative of a broader shift in the company's creative direction, but only time will tell how WWE chooses to evolve its product in the years to come.

As fans eagerly await the future of sports entertainment, one thing is certain: the landscape of WWE is always evolving, and the only constant is change.